"'''Bring Us Together'''" was a political slogan popularized after the election of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate [[Richard Nixon]] as [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[United States presidential election, 1968|in 1968]]. The text was derived from a sign carried by 13-year-old Vicki Lynne Cole at Nixon's rally in her home town of [[Deshler, Ohio]] during the campaign.

The sign, which read "Bring Us Together Again" was seen by Nixon or a member of his staff, and Nixon adopted the phrase "Bring Us Together" in his victory speech on November 6, 1968 as representing his administration's initial goal<U+2014>to reunify the bitterly divided country.  Cole came forward as the person who carried the sign, and was the subject of intense media attention.

Nixon invited Cole and her family to the [[First inauguration of Richard Nixon|inauguration]], and she appeared on a float in the Inaugural Parade.  The phrase "Bring Us Together" was used ironically by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] when Nixon proposed policies they considered divisive.  Cole refused to comment on Nixon's 1974 resignation, but later expressed her sympathy for him.  Nixon speechwriter [[William Safire]], who originally inserted the phrase in draft speeches written for Nixon, later expressed doubt that Cole's sign ever existed.

==Background==
The 1968 presidential campaign was one of the most bitterly fought in the nation's history.  Set among national divisions over the [[Vietnam War]], social policy, and against the backdrop of riot and assassination,<ref name = "upi">{{Cite web
  | title = 1968 Presidential Election
  | work = 1968 Year in Review
  | publisher = upi.com
  | date = 1968
  | url = http://www.upi.com/Audio/Year_in_Review/Events-of-1968/1968-Presidential-Election/12303153093431-2/
  | accessdate =2010<U+2013>09<U+2013>14 }}</ref> none of the campaigns made healing divisions a major theme<U+2014>an early slogan by Democratic candidate [[Hubert Humphrey]], "United With Humphrey" had been scrapped.<ref name = "safire"/>  The President, Democrat [[Lyndon Baines Johnson]] (often called L.B.J.) could give Humphrey little support due to his own personal unpopularity.<ref>{{Cite news 
  | last = Wise
  | first = David
  | title = The Twilight of a President
  | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]
  | page = SM125
  | date = 1968<U+2013>11<U+2013>03
  | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0F1EF63E5F127A93C1A9178AD95F4C8685F9&scp=1&sq=the+twilight+of+a+president+johnson&st=p
  | accessdate =2010<U+2013>09<U+2013>15 }} (fee for article)</ref>

By 1968, candidates were appealing to the electorate through television, rather than through whistle-stop train tours.<ref>{{Citation
  | last = Mickelson
  | first = Sig
  | title = The Electric Mirror:  Politics in an Age of Television
  | publisher = Dodd, Mead
  | date = 1972
  | location = New York, N.Y.
  | page = 103
  | isbn =0396063632 }}</ref>  Nixon had included them in his past national campaigns<U+2014>he had broken off one such tour in 1952 to make the [[Checkers speech]],<ref>{{Citation
 |last=Morris|first=Roger|date=1990|title=Richard Milhous Nixon: The Rise of an American Politician|publisher=Henry Holt and Company|isbn=0805018344
  | location = New York, N.Y.
  | pages = 808<U+2013>809}}</ref> and in 1960, had stopped at Deshler.  The rural Ohio village, about {{convert|45|mi}} southwest of [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]], was popular among whistle-stopping presidential candidates as two main lines of the [[Baltimore & Ohio Railroad]] crossed there<U+2014>other visitors in search of votes had included [[Al Smith]], [[Harry Truman]], and [[Barry Goldwater]].<ref name = "joe"/>  Deshler voters would respond in 1968 by giving Nixon an overwhelming majority of their votes.<ref name = "blade"/>

==Rally and sign==
[[File:Deshschool.JPG|thumb|left|Deshler High and Grade School (today Deshler Elementary School), which Cole attended]]
Cole was an eighth grader in Deshler; her father was the local Methodist minister while her mother taught third grade.<ref name = "times">{{Citation
  | last = Ripley
  | first = Anthony
  | title = Ohio girl, 13, recalls "Bring Us Together" placard
  | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]
  | date = 1968<U+2013>11<U+2013>08
  | url = http://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=FB061FF63E54157493CAA9178AD95F4C8685F9
  | accessdate = 2009-05-05}} (fee for article)</ref>  On October 22, 1968, the day of Nixon's stop in Deshler, Cole attended eighth-grade class as usual. During the morning session, one of her teachers announced that any girls interested in being "Nixonettes" (girls asked to cheer and provide atmosphere at the rally) should report to the fire station after school. Cole did so, along with her friend, Rita Bowman, and the girls were provided with paper red, white, and blue dresses (to be worn over other clothing) and signs. Cole's said, "L.B.J. Convinced Us<U+2014>Vote Republican".<ref name = "times"/>

That afternoon, Cole attended the rally, wearing her dress and holding her sign. The Nixon train pulled in, and the police lowered the rope which kept the crowd clear of the tracks. As the crowd surged forward, Cole dropped her sign amidst the pushing and shoving.<ref name = "post">{{Citation
  | title = Girl gave Nixon theme
  | newspaper = [[The Washington Post]]
  | date = 1968<U+2013>11<U+2013>07
  | url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/display_pdf.pdf?filename=/share3/pqimage/hnirs103/20090505174406714/23505/out.pdf
  | accessdate = 2009-05-05}} (fee for article)</ref>  Instead of picking up her sign, Cole pushed forward to get close to the train, and as she neared the train, she saw another sign on the ground, face down. She picked it up and displayed it without even reading it.<ref name = "times"/>

Cole observed Nixon, who gave a speech from the rear platform, and thought he was a good family man, looking warm and friendly and appearing much as she expected him to. She did not even look at the sign until she was teased about it by a classmate, who suggested the sign, "Bring Us Together Again" was about boys, not politics. She kept the dress, but threw away the sign.<ref name = "times"/>

==Nixon speeches and inauguration==
[[File:deshrr.jpg|thumb|right|The Deshler, Ohio railroad station, as seen in 2009]]
Nixon speechwriter [[William Safire]] had been told of the sign by  a friend of Nixon, Richard Moore, who often left the train at campaign stops to mingle with the crowd<ref name = "safire"/> and seek items of local color for the speechwriters to use.   Safire stated in his book on the early days of the Nixon administration (originally published in 1975) that at Deshler, "Moore boarded the train with that mystic look that a writer gets when he has something delicious to work with, some piece of color that could be more than a gimmick."<ref>{{Citation
  | last = Safire
  | first = William
  | authorlink = William Safire
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Before the Fall:  An Inside View of the pre-Watergate White House
  | publisher = Transaction Publishers
  | date = 2005
  | location = Piscataway, N.J.
  | page = 82
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=4yPRj_ZQNSYC&dq=Bring+Us+Together+Nixon
  | accessdate = 2010<U+2013>10<U+2013>08
  | isbn = 1412804663 }}</ref>  According to Safire in a 2007 column, Moore stuck his head into the compartment occupied by Nixon's speechwriters and stated,  "There<U+2019>s a little kid out there with a hand-lettered sign that I think says 'Bring Us Together'."<ref name = "lima"/>  Safire wrote in that column that he inserted the phrase into Nixon's remarks for the speech to be given at the next stop.<ref name = "lima">{{Citation
 | last = Safire
  | first = William
  | title = On Language ("The Way Forward")
  | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]
  | date = 2007<U+2013>09<U+2013>02
  | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/02/magazine/02wwln-safire-t.html?scp=1&sq=bring+us+together+safire&st=nyt
  |accessdate =2010<U+2013>09<U+2013>21
  }}</ref>

Nixon used the phrase in concluding a rally at [[Madison Square Garden]] on October 31, 1968.  Recalling the visit to Deshler, the Republican candidate stated, "There were many signs like those I see here.  But one sign held by a teenager said, 'Bring Us Together Again'. My friends, America needs to be brought together."<ref name = "seventies">{{Citation
  | last = Schulman
  | first = Bruce J.
  | title = The seventies: the great shift in American culture, society, and politics
  | publisher = Da Capo Press
  | date = 2002
  | location = Cambridge, Mass.
  | page = 23
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=4yPRj_ZQNSYC&dq=Bring+Us+Together+Nixon
  | accessdate = 2010<U+2013>09<U+2013>11
  | isbn =030681126X }}</ref>  However, Nixon's use of the phrase received little coverage until after the election.<ref name = "safire"/>  On hearing of Nixon's Madison Square Garden speech, Deshler school officials asked students about the sign, to no avail.<ref name = "joe"/>
  Safire included the incident in a draft victory statement, which Nixon looked at before addressing the nation as [[President-elect of the United States|President-elect]].<ref name = "safire">{{Citation
 | last = Safire
 | first = William
 | title = Safire's Political Dictionary
 | publisher = Oxford University Press (US)
 | location = New York, N.Y.
 | year = 2008
 | page = 83
 | isbn = 0195343344
 | url = http://books.google.com/?id=jK-0NPoMiYoC
 | accessdate = 2010-09-14}}</ref>  In his victory speech on November 6, Nixon recalled the sign:<blockquote>
I saw many signs in this campaign, some of them were not friendly; some of them were very friendly. But the one that touched me the most was one that I saw in Deshler, Ohio, at the end of a long day of whistle-stopping.  A little town. I suppose five times the population was there in the dusk. It was almost impossible to see, but a teenager held up a sign, "Bring us together."  And that will be the great objective of this administration at the outset, to bring the American people together.<ref name = "evans"/>
</blockquote>

Reconciliation among the American people was also a theme of Humphrey's concession statement.  "I have done my best. I have lost, Mr. Nixon has won. The democratic process has worked its will, so now let's get on with the urgent task of uniting our country."<ref name = "upi"/>

Deshler school officials asked students again about the sign after Nixon mentioned his visit to Deshler in the victory speech, and this time Cole came forward.  She stated that she had not done so before as she had not written the sign.<ref name = "joe">{{Citation
  | last = Ionne
  | first = Joe
  | title = Vicki hopes to see Nixon inaugurated
  | newspaper = [[The Columbus Dispatch]]
  | date = 1968<U+2013>11<U+2013>09
  | page = 26A}}</ref>  Reporters interviewed the girl in the principal's office. Cole stated that she felt that Nixon was the one who could bring the country together again.<ref name = "joe"/>  She also indicated that being interviewed by reporters from Washington, New York, and Chicago was more fun than sitting in history class.<ref name = "times"/>  The [[The Blade (newspaper)|Toledo ''Blade'']] investigated the matter, but could not ascertain who made the sign, or what happened to it after Cole discarded it.  John Baer, village chief of police, stated, "I think this has to be the most important thing that has ever happened around here."<ref name = "blade"/>  Paul Scharf, editor of Deshler's weekly newspaper, ''The Flag'', stated that he did not believe the mystery of the sign's origin or fate would ever be cleared up.<ref name = "blade">{{Citation
 | last = Yourist
  | first = Leonard
  | title = Deshler citizens blushing under national gaze
  | newspaper = [[Toledo Blade|The Blade (Toledo, Ohio)]]
  | date = 1968<U+2013>11<U+2013>08
  | page = 1
  | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PCcxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pAEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5337,1531353&hl=en
  |accessdate = 2010<U+2013>09<U+2013>21
  }}</ref>  Safire states that he was told by Moore that the sign stood out as obviously handmade and not produced by the local Nixon campign.<ref name = "safire"/>

On November 19, 1968, campaign special assistant and longtime Nixon advisor [[Murray Chotiner]] proposed inviting the Cole family to the inauguration and having Vicki Cole ride the theme float.<ref>{{Cite web
  | last = Chotiner
  | first = Murray
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Memo from Murray Chotiner to H.R. Haldeman and John Mitchell (November 19, 1968) in Box 19, Folder 1 (Virtual Library)
  | work = Nixon Presidential Returned Materials Collection: White House Special Files (WHSF)
  | publisher = Richard Nixon Presidential Library and Museum
  | date = 1968<U+2013>11<U+2013>19
  | url = http://www.nixonlibrary.gov/virtuallibrary/documents/whsfreturned/WHSF_Box_19/WHSF19-01.pdf
  | accessdate =2010<U+2013>09<U+2013>03 }}</ref>  The President-elect subsequently invited Reverend and Mrs. Cole and their family to attend the inauguration.<ref>{{Citation
  | title = Ohio girl who held up sign invited to capital by Nixon
  | newspaper =[[The New York Times]]
  | date = 1968<U+2013>12<U+2013>04
  | url = http://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=FB0715FD355C147493C6A91789D95F4C8685F9
  | accessdate = 2009-05-05}} (fee for article)</ref>  The family was brought to Washington by the Inaugural Committee.<ref>{{Citation
  | title = Washington awaits the inauguration
  | periodical = [[The New York Times]]
  | date = 1969<U+2013>01<U+2013>19
  | url = http://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F60715F73E5D137A93CBA8178AD85F4D8685F9
  | accessdate = 2009-05-05}} (fee for article)</ref>  Vicki Cole carried a recreation of her sign on one of the floats in the inaugural parade.<ref>{{Citation
  | title = Toward the Nixon inauguration
  | periodical = [[Time (magazine)|Time]]
  | date =1969<U+2013>01<U+2013>17
  | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,838850,00.html
  | accessdate = 2009-05-05}}</ref>
{{Panorama |image=File:Bring Us Together.jpg|height=400|alt=|caption=The Ohio float, recreating Nixon's visit to Deshler, passes by the presidential reviewing stand.}}

Carla Garrity, a fourteen-year-old girl from [[Burbank, California]], objected to Cole's invitation to the inauguration on the ground that Cole had done nothing to deserve it.  In a letter to her congressman, [[Ed Reinecke]], Garrity stated that she had worked very hard for Nixon and other Republican candidates:  "Therefore, I am very much against that 13 year old girl in Ohio who held up the sign 'Bring us Together' being invited to the inaugural.  She didn't even ''read'' or ''write'' it!"<ref>{{Cite web
  | last = Garrity
  | first = Carla
  | title = Letter to Congressman Ed Reinecke
  | work = Nixon Presidential Returned Materials Collection: White House Special Files (WHSF) Box 19, Folder 3 (Virtual Library)  | publisher = Richard Nixon Presidential Library and Museum
  | date = 1968<U+2013>11<U+2013>17
  | url = http://www.nixonlibrary.gov/virtuallibrary/documents/whsfreturned/WHSF_Box_19/WHSF19-03.pdf
  | accessdate =2010<U+2013>09<U+2013>15 }}</ref>  Reinecke forwarded the letter to Nixon aide [[John Ehrlichman]] with the comment, "I suspect that Carla's reaction may be shared by other young people who worked in the Nixon campaign".<ref>{{Cite web
  | last = Reinecke
  | first = Ed
  | title = Memo to John Ehrlichman
  | work = Nixon Presidential Returned Materials Collection: White House Special Files (WHSF)
   | publisher = Richard Nixon Presidential Library and Museum
  | date = 1968<U+2013>12<U+2013>03
  | url = http://www.nixonlibrary.gov/virtuallibrary/documents/whsfreturned/WHSF_Box_19/WHSF19-03.pdf
  | accessdate =2010<U+2013>09<U+2013>15 }}</ref>  Nixon assistant [[Charles E. Stuart]] replied to Reinecke, stating "Vicki Lynne has been invited to the inauguration not because she carried the sign, or even because she made the sign, but rather because the sign which she did carry proved to be an inspiration to Mr. Nixon" and expressed his confidence that the invitation would be well received by other young Nixon partisans.<ref>{{Cite web
  | last = Stuart
  | first = Charles E
  | title = Letter to Congressman Ed Reinecke
  | work = Nixon Presidential Returned Materials Collection: White House Special Files (WHSF)
Box 19, Folder 3 (Virtual Library)  
| publisher = Richard Nixon Presidential Library and Museum
  | date = 1968<U+2013>12<U+2013>17
  | url = http://www.nixonlibrary.gov/virtuallibrary/documents/whsfreturned/WHSF_Box_19/WHSF19-03.pdf
  | accessdate =2010<U+2013>09<U+2013>15 }}</ref>

==Political usage and aftermath==
[[File:Deshfire.jpg|thumb|right|Deshler, Ohio fire department, where the "Nixonettes" assembled]]
The Inaugural Committee wanted to adopt "Bring Us Together" as the inaugural theme, appalling Safire, who said, "That wasn't the theme of the campaign."<ref name = "evans">{{Citation
  | last = Evans
  | first = Rowland
  | last2 = Novak
  | first2 = Robert
  | pages = 33<U+2013>34
  | title =Nixon in the White House: The Frustration of Power
  | publisher = Random House
  | location = New York, N.Y.
  | year = 1971
  | isbn = 0394462734
  | accessdate = }}</ref>  Safire and other aides felt that the administration should seek progress, not unity,<ref name = "lima"/> and White House Chief of Staff-designate [[H.R. Haldeman]] managed to get the theme changed to "Forward Together."  Nevertheless, the phrase "Bring Us Together" was thrown in the face of the Nixon administration by Democrats each time something divisive was proposed, and was used as the title of a tell-all expose by [[Leon Panetta]] after he was fired from the Nixon administration for dissenting from the White House's "[[Southern strategy]]" on [[civil rights]] policy.<ref name = "evans"/> 

Nixon's advisors denied that he had abandoned a desire to bring the American people together.<ref>{{Citation
  | last = Sidey
  | first = Hugh
  | authorlink = Hugh Sidey
  | title = Nixon in a crisis of leadership
  | journal = Life
  | volume = 68
  | pages =28<U+2013>29
  | date = May 15, 1970
  | year = 1970
  | accessdate = 2010<U+2013>10<U+2013>08 }}</ref>  However, they were divided between those who sought national unity, and those, such as campaign manager and [[Attorney General of the United States|Attorney General]] [[John N. Mitchell]], who felt that Nixon should concentrate on keeping the voters who had cast their ballots for him, and should seek to win over the voters who had favored third-party candidate Alabama Governor [[George Wallace]], as the key to reelection in 1972.<ref>{{Citation
  | last = Drew
  | first = Elizabeth
  | authorlink = Elizabeth Drew
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Richard M. Nixon
  | publisher = Macmillan
  | date = 2007
  | location = New York, N.J.
  | pages = 35<U+2013>36
  | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=OLBC9xLD0zYC&source=gbs_navlinks_s
  | accessdate = 2010<U+2013>10<U+2013>08
  | isbn = 1412804663 }}</ref>  According to Safire, after taking office, Nixon and his advisors decided that he need not bring the country together, but need only work to secure his reelection by appealing to voters who were not hostile to Nixon and his policies<U+2014>they became known as the [[Silent Majority]].<ref>{{Citation
  | last = Safire
  | first = William
  | authorlink = William Safire
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Before the Fall:  An Inside View of the pre-Watergate White House
  | publisher = Transaction Publishers
  | date = 2005
  | location = Piscataway, N.J.
  | pages = 308<U+2013>310
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=4yPRj_ZQNSYC&dq=Bring+Us+Together+Nixon
  | accessdate = 2010<U+2013>10<U+2013>08
  | isbn = 1412804663 }}</ref>  Historian [[Stanley Kutler]] suggested in his book on the Nixon administration that Nixon's policies widened divisions in America, but that the nation finally came together late in his presidency<U+2014>to reject Nixon and demand his removal.<ref>{{Citation
  | last = Kutler
  | first = Stanley
  | authorlink = Stanley Kutler
  | coauthors = 
  | title = The wars of Watergate: the last crisis of Richard Nixon
  | publisher = W.W. Norton & Co.
  | date = 1992
  | location = New York
  | pages = 10, 414
  | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=k2U9w6RVpowC&source=gbs_navlinks_s
  | accessdate = 2010<U+2013>10<U+2013>08
  | isbn = 0393308278 }}</ref>

In late 1970, Vicki Cole indicated in an interview that Nixon was doing the best that he could.<ref>{{Citation
  | title = Vicki Cole keeps faith in President
  | newspaper = [[The Bryan Times]]
  | date = 1970<U+2013>05<U+2013>12
  | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=799&dat=19700512&id=OncJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=I0gDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4110,2509731
  | accessdate = 2009-05-06}}</ref>  During the 1972 campaign, Cole served as Ohio chair of a future voters organization for the Nixon campaign.  She then left politics, devoting her spare time to training and showing horses. <ref name = "la"/>  In 1974, Cole declined to comment on the resignation of President Nixon in the wake of the [[Watergate scandal]],<ref>{{Citation
  | title = 'Forward Together' girl quiet on Nixon
  | newspaper = [[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]
  | date = 1974<U+2013>08<U+2013>09
  | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7wIOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Vm0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7134,981694&hl=en
  | accessdate = 2010-09-14}}</ref>
but stated in 1977 that she felt sympathy for him, though she believed his resignation was necessary.<ref name = "la">{{Citation
  | title = 'Bring-Us-Together' girl asks, 'Which way now?'
  | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]]
  | date = 1977<U+2013>01<U+2013>17
  | url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/645916762.html?dids=645916762:645916762&FMT=AI&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+17%2C+1977&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(1886-Current+File)&desc=Bring-Us-Together+Girl+Asks+%27Which+Way+Now%3F%27
  | accessdate = 2009-05-06}} (fee for article)</ref>

Safire, in his political dictionary published in 2008, recollected that when he asked Moore, some years after the inauguration, whether he had really seen the girl holding the sign, or whether he had imagined it, "his eyes took on a faraway look".<ref name = "safire"/>  In columns written in his final years before his 2009 death, Safire commented that the sign was "almost too good to be true",<ref>{{Citation
 | last = Safire
  | first = William
  | title = On Language ("Fired Up")
  | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]
  | date = 2008<U+2013>01<U+2013>20
  | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/20/magazine/20wwln-safire-t.html?scp=2&sq=bring+us+together+safire&st=nyt
  |accessdate =2010<U+2013>09<U+2013>21
  }}</ref> and said of Moore, "<nowiki>[h]</nowiki>e may have made that up".<ref name = "lima"/>

